\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Addressing
\series default
.
 Addresses packets with IP addresses of the destination.
 Configures end devices with unique IP address for identification on the
 network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Encapsulation
\series default
.
 Receives a protocol data unit (PDU) from the transport layer.
 The network layer then adds IP header information, such as the IP address
 of source & destination hosts.
 The PDU now is called a packet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Routing
\series default
.
 Routes the packet to the correct destination.
 Intermediary devices such as routers help to select paths and direct packets
 to destination host in a process known as routing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Decapsulation
\series default
.
 When the packet arrives at the destination host, the host checks the IP
 header of the packet and verifies that it matches its own IP address.
 The host decapsulates packets and pass it to the upper layers for further
 interpretation at the destination end device.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
